{"title_page": "Renault R", "text_new": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Renault R-series\n| image = FRANCIS CANY ROYER.JPG\n| caption = Late eighties Renault R340\n| manufacturer = [[Renault Trucks]]\n| aka = [[Ford Transcontinental]]<br>Saipa Diesel R-Series (Iran)\n| production = 1980-1996\n| assembly = \n| predecessor = Berliet KB 2400\n| successor =[[Renault Premium]]\n| class = Heavy truck\n| body_style = [[Cab Over Engine|COE]]\n| layout =\n| platform =\n| engine = [[Straight-six engine]]<br>* G-series (9.8&nbsp;L)<br>* G-series (12&nbsp;L)<br>[[V8 engine]] (14.88&nbsp;L)\n| transmission =  \n| wheelbase =\n| length =\n| width =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| related = [[Ford Transcontinental]]\n| designer =\n}}\n\nThe '''Renault R-series''' was a range of [[heavy-duty truck]]s built by Renault V\u00e9hicles Industrielles (RVI) from 1980 until 1996. The cabin was Berliet's KB 2400 model, originally introduced in 1977. The fusion of [[Saviem]] and [[Berliet]] into RVI brought with it a consolidation of the lineups, although the Saviem and Berliet badges continued to be used for some time. The KB 2400 cabin was also used for Ford's [[Ford Transcontinental|Transcontinental]].<ref name=testspecial>{{cite journal | journal = TRUCK | date = December 1986 | ref = truck1286 | page = 75 | editor-last = Barden | editor-first = Paul | title = Test Special: Renault R340 Turboliner | location = London, UK | publisher = FF Publishing Ltd }}</ref> The R-series ranged from the smallest R280 to the V8-powered R420.\n\n==History==\nOriginally built by Berliet, the truck became the top-of-the-line offering in Renault's new heavy commercial vehicle line. Sold as the R-series, it offered a range of engines in models from the original R310 up to the V8-engined R420. Most models were inline-sixes. The R-series overlapped the more compact, more utilitarian G-series, and was meant for longer distance journeys where driver comfort is of more importance.<ref name=testspecial74>[[#truck1286|''TRUCK'', December 1986]], p. 74</ref>\n\n[[File:Renault R 358 Ti Major 1997 (19103292876).jpg|thumb|left|1997 Renault R385 ti Major]]\nThe {{convert|338|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}} R340 appeared at the 1986 [[Paris Motor Show|Paris Salon]], being a modified version of the twelve-litre inline-six also used in the R310.<ref name=testspecial74/> A high-roofed model with a bonded and riveted fibreglass extension called the Turboliner was also sold, beginning in 1986.<ref name=testspecial74/> In 1990 the R-series received a facelift, with a body-colored grille and a more aerodynamic appearance.<ref name=lignard>{{cite web | url = http://lelignard.canalblog.com/archives/2012/05/09/24217867.html | title = La gamme R de Renault |trans-title=Renault's R series | language = French | date = 2012-05-09 | work = Le blog du lignard }}</ref> IN 1992 the lie was renamed '''Renault Major'''. In 1996, the R-series was replaced by the new [[Renault Premium]].\n\n===Engines===\nThe R was mostly equipped with Renault's 12-litre G-series inline-six turbodiesel, although some higher powered models (R360, 370, 390, 420) received a 14.88&nbsp;L V8 unit. The smaller 9.8&nbsp;liter G-series engine was also available in the R330 and the R340&nbsp;ti. The most powerful six was the {{convert|385|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}} R385&nbsp;ti of the 1990s. Eight-cylinder models' bodyshell was actually coded  KB 2480.<ref name=lignard/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Renault R series}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Renault Trucks}}\n{{Renault Trucks timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Renault trucks|R]]\n[[Category:Berliet]]\n[[Category:Vehicles introduced in 1980]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Renault R-series\n| image = FRANCIS CANY ROYER.JPG\n| caption = Late eighties Renault R340\n| manufacturer = [[Renault Trucks]]\n| aka = [[Ford Transcontinental]]\n| production = 1980-1996\n| assembly = \n| predecessor = Berliet KB 2400\n| successor =[[Renault Premium]]\n| class = Heavy truck\n| body_style = [[Cab Over Engine|COE]]\n| layout =\n| platform =\n| engine = [[Straight-six engine]]<br>* G-series (9.8&nbsp;L)<br>* G-series (12&nbsp;L)<br>[[V8 engine]] (14.88&nbsp;L)\n| transmission =  \n| wheelbase =\n| length =\n| width =\n| height =\n| weight =\n| related = [[Ford Transcontinental]]\n| designer =\n}}\n\nThe '''Renault R-series''' was a range of [[heavy-duty truck]]s built by Renault V\u00e9hicles Industrielles (RVI) from 1980 until 1996. The cabin was Berliet's KB 2400 model, originally introduced in 1977. The fusion of [[Saviem]] and [[Berliet]] into RVI brought with it a consolidation of the lineups, although the Saviem and Berliet badges continued to be used for some time. The KB 2400 cabin was also used for Ford's [[Ford Transcontinental|Transcontinental]].<ref name=testspecial>{{cite journal | journal = TRUCK | date = December 1986 | ref = truck1286 | page = 75 | editor-last = Barden | editor-first = Paul | title = Test Special: Renault R340 Turboliner | location = London, UK | publisher = FF Publishing Ltd }}</ref> The R-series ranged from the smallest R280 to the V8-powered R420.\n\n==History==\nOriginally built by Berliet, the truck became the top-of-the-line offering in Renault's new heavy commercial vehicle line. Sold as the R-series, it offered a range of engines in models from the original R310 up to the V8-engined R420. Most models were inline-sixes. The R-series overlapped the more compact, more utilitarian G-series, and was meant for longer distance journeys where driver comfort is of more importance.<ref name=testspecial74>[[#truck1286|''TRUCK'', December 1986]], p. 74</ref>\n\n[[File:Renault R 358 Ti Major 1997 (19103292876).jpg|thumb|left|1997 Renault R385 ti Major]]\nThe {{convert|338|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}} R340 appeared at the 1986 [[Paris Motor Show|Paris Salon]], being a modified version of the twelve-litre inline-six also used in the R310.<ref name=testspecial74/> A high-roofed model with a bonded and riveted fibreglass extension called the Turboliner was also sold, beginning in 1986.<ref name=testspecial74/> In 1990 the R-series received a facelift, with a body-colored grille and a more aerodynamic appearance.<ref name=lignard>{{cite web | url = http://lelignard.canalblog.com/archives/2012/05/09/24217867.html | title = La gamme R de Renault |trans-title=Renault's R series | language = French | date = 2012-05-09 | work = Le blog du lignard }}</ref> IN 1992 the lie was renamed '''Renault Major'''. In 1996, the R-series was replaced by the new [[Renault Premium]].\n\n===Engines===\nThe R was mostly equipped with Renault's 12-litre G-series inline-six turbodiesel, although some higher powered models (R360, 370, 390, 420) received a 14.88&nbsp;L V8 unit. The smaller 9.8&nbsp;liter G-series engine was also available in the R330 and the R340&nbsp;ti. The most powerful six was the {{convert|385|PS|kW|0|abbr=on}} R385&nbsp;ti of the 1990s. Eight-cylinder models' bodyshell was actually coded  KB 2480.<ref name=lignard/>\n{{clear left}}\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Renault R series}}\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Renault Trucks}}\n{{Renault Trucks timeline}}\n\n[[Category:Renault trucks|R]]\n[[Category:Berliet]]\n[[Category:Vehicles introduced in 1980]]\n", "name_user": "110.138.150.166", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Renault_R"}
